          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Logan, Utah  5/15/2003<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347'>Daniel "Dartax" Burke</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 17, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Mystic Comics<br />
5-15-2003<br />
<br />
As I promised myself this year, I drove outside my usual territory and went to play Magi-Nation elsewhere inside the state of Utah. Having checked the website for the tournament time and address, I drove to Logan to where they were having a tournament at Mystic Comics. Just my bad luck, it was raining just before the tournament, so this may have hindered turnout. Although, they said its been falling off with the big gap between leagues.<br />
<br />
Being the stranger I had to raise my hand when they were looking for a fourth player. So, I met Danielle, Scott, and Brady. Pairings were assigned and it was decided to go three rounds.<br />
<br />
Round 1<br />
Danielle was my first opponent. She told me that she hasn&#8217;t played for a while, about a month. This may have been a big factor in the game. Her Nar deck starts off with Erisa. However, since most of my deck is effect driven with only a few powers, freezing the creatures made no difference and Delia forced her way through Erisa and Fray. Delia even made trouble for Laranel, her third magi. I remember using all of Delia&#8217;s energize to play a couple Storm Cloud on a couple creatures on two separate turns. Painful to pay Laranel&#8217;s penalty, but the Storm Shield was in play and took advantage of my magi with zero energy.<br />
<br />
Scott faced off against Brady. Apparently, they had already finished when Danielle and I completed our game. Scott had won with Naroom taking on the Dark Twins.<br />
<br />
Pos.<br />
Adding in the Hurricane Orish really helped the Arderian Adept deck, even if it was Delia doing the work.<br />
Neg.<br />
Danielle wasn&#8217;t able to freeze her relics before Erisa was defeated, costing her the Ice Lens in play. Also, she didn&#8217;t draw many of the cards she needed, or they showed up when it was too late.<br />
<br />
Round 2<br />
Scott has an interesting Naroom deck. At least, I&#8217;ve never faced anything like it before. Tiller showed up first, so I took the magi out as fast as I could. I know Tiller can be dangerous when fueling a good deck with his card draw. Most of his deck was Naroom, so I was a bit surprised when he played Warrior&#8217;s Boots and an Ormagon to wipe out the swarm I was building with Arderian Adept. When he threw out Yaki&#8217;s Gauntlets and used its power, I expected at least one Wasperine. However, he had the two Wasperines he needed to defeat Shimmer. In the end, the game came down to Shivara and his last magi. He ended up using Essence of Naroom to take my only Paradwyn creature in play, Aerial Flist. If the relic&#8217;s power would&#8217;ve allowed it to attack that turn, he could&#8217;ve won by simply destroying all my non-Illusionary creatures in play. But, since it couldn&#8217;t, I had Brannix attack the Arderial creature he now controlled. So, the advantage was short lived, and Shivara managed to pull the win.<br />
<br />
In the other game, Danielle lost to Brady.<br />
<br />
Pos.<br />
A Naroom deck that used Ormagon with Warrior&#8217;s Boots and following up with the Wasperines. Real smooth.<br />
Neg.<br />
I have to say Danielle&#8217;s Nar deck seems to be struggling.<br />
<br />
Round 3<br />
In games against the Dark Twins so far, my Arderian Adept deck usually softens them up with Delia and Shimmer crushes the twins and the final core magi quite nicely. Well, as to be expected when facing the twins, Brady went first. He started with Dream Rift and ended up playing two copies of Wudge. Something very dangerous for Delia to face when playing out a Vellup swarm. Since I only pull the one starting card, I was very lucky to pull a Sandswirl and Abwyn&#8217;s Gift in the starting hand. I used Sandswirl on the smaller of the two, played the swarm as usual, and followed up with Abwyn&#8217;s Gift for the bigger one. He then took out Delia by playing two Core Grag, after attacking the Elder Vellup. Arderian Adept finished off the Dark Twins after a few turns, actually undreaming his Shadow Hyren on her first turn in play. By the time she was done with the twins, Morag flipped over to face off against more than 21 energy in creatures, and Shimmer with eight (which turned into thirteen thanks to the Hurricane Orish when he used Dream Rift).<br />
<br />
While I didn&#8217;t see end of their game, Danielle&#8217;s Nar deck won against Scott. With his creature powers costing one more, he couldn&#8217;t use the Ormagon or the Weebo&#8217;s power without first adding energy to them. And, those were two of his key cards.<br />
<br />
Pos.<br />
Danielle&#8217;s Nar deck finally finding its niche.<br />
Neg.<br />
Brady actually started with Entomb, and did not use it. I will grant him this much, he probably didn&#8217;t know what to Entomb.<br />
<br />
Because the other three players actually all had one win, there was a three-way tie for second place. As a bonus, since we had paid an entry fee, the store threw in several booster packs as prize support, with all three second place winners getting one pack each. However, all we had to choose from was the Unlimited Base Set, as their distributor is out of everything else.<br />
<br />
Before I left, I received a Magi-Nation cap. Eric Pace, the tournament director, recalled that the store had a few left. He told me that they had been given a stack of them a while back, during one of the storyline tournaments, and they&#8217;ve been using them as prize support for players that win a tournament at their store (limit one per player). Although I&#8217;ve won tournaments elsewhere, it was my first time at Mystic Comics. So, now I have a cap to declare my addiction. And, the people were great too. <br />
<br />
I stayed and visited for a bit before driving back home. <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/treports/treports.php?id=4414&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
